<code>            (isy bhi codeblock bnta ha)
x=4
</code>


(agr ``` backticks waly m naam ni likhengy python java ya markdown tb bhi wo blockcode hi consider hoga but lnaguage likhny se colors ajany jese python m varibale ka color alg hota 
data type ka alg to wo color ajany)
```markdown        (isy bhi code block lgta h markdown ki jagah python likhdo ya java to ussi ka codeblock bn jana
> hey
```

summary:
The triple backticks (```) start and end a code block.
<code>...</code> is HTML code tag, also used to display code in Markdown.

---------------Both methods (backticks and <code>) are valid for showing code in Markdown ‚Äî
Backticks ‚Üí Markdown syntax
<code> ‚Üí HTML syntax inside Markdown


---------------------Code----------------------------
To denote a word or phrase as code, enclose it in backticks (`).(triple backticks multiple lines ko blockcode bnany keliye or single backtick kisi word ka phrase ko blockcode bnany 
keliye use krty hn)

Markdown	                                                                HTML	                                              Rendered Output
At the command prompt, type `nano`.	                    At the command prompt, type <code>nano</code>.	                At the command prompt, type nano.
(output m srf nano word blockcode bna hua hoga)         (output m srf nano word blockcode bna hua hoga)


----------------------Escaping Backticks-----------------------
If the word or phrase you want to denote as code includes one or more backticks, you can escape it by enclosing the word or phrase in double backticks (``).

Markdown	                                                                    HTML	                                            Rendered Output
``Use `code` in your Markdown file.``                    	<code>Use `code` in your Markdown file.</code>	                Use `code` in your Markdown file.
(puri line blockcode hogi lekin us m code jo                 (puri line blockcode hogi lekin us m code jo 
 word h uske agay pichy backticks ajany)                      word h uske agay pichy backticks ajany)



--------------------------Code Blocks
To create code blocks, indent every line of the block by at least four spaces or one tab.(starting m 4 spaces dedo ya ek tab dedo tb bhi yh blockcode bnjana)

    <html>
      <head>
      </head>
    </html>

The rendered output looks like this:(yh block code hi bnega)
<html>
  <head>
  </head>
</html>



----------------------Horizontal Rules
To create a horizontal rule(line), use three or more asterisks (***), dashes (---), or underscores (___) on a line by themselves.

***

---

___

(agr 1 ya 2 dalengy *,-,_ to wo text hi consider hoga to zrori h teeno ko 3 rkhyn ya usy zyada )
The rendered output of all three looks identical(teeno se line hi bnegi)



--------------------------Horizontal Rule Best Practices
For compatibility, put blank lines before and after horizontal rules.

‚úÖ  Do this	
Try to put a blank line before...

---

...and after a horizontal rule.


‚ùå  Don't do this
Without blank lines, this would be a heading.(blank line ni dalengy to yh wali line heading bn jani kunke kisi bhi line ky nichy --- hiphen lgao to wo heading bnany ka tareeka h)
---
Don't do this!


--------------------------Links--------------------
(ham direct link bhi paste krskty hn or wo link click hokr open bhi hogi but uska mtlb hua hamy markdown ni ata to isiliye yh format krna h link paste krny keliye)
To create a link, enclose the link text in brackets (e.g., [Duck Duck Go]) and then follow it immediately with the URL in parentheses (e.g., (https://duckduckgo.com)).

My favorite search engine is [Duck Duck Go](https://duckduckgo.com).(isy yh hoga jese word m ham kch likhty or agr ham chahty wo link bny to right click krke link paste krdety to 
test ka color blue hojata or wo link bn jati isi trh Duck Duck Go ko likhny ky foran bd link dedengy to wo link bn jani 

OUTPUT:
My favorite search engine is Duck Duck Go.(Duck Duck Go ka color blue hojana yh link bn jaygi


-----------------------------Adding Titles-----------------------------
You can optionally add a title for a link. This will appear as a tooltip when the user hovers over the link. To add a title, enclose it in quotation marks after the URL.

My favorite search engine is [Duck Duck Go](https://duckduckgo.com "The best search engine for privacy").(yh jo link aygi us per jb cursor lekr jyngy to hover krny per likha aygathe best 
search engine for privacy isi trh image paste krke bhi jo link h uske agay "" double quotation m jo bhi likhengy wo hover se ajana jb cursor lekr jyngy image per tb)


OUTPUT:
My favorite search engine is Duck Duck Go.(Duck Duck Go YH link to h or hover krny per text likha bhi ana)



--------------------URLs and Email Addresses------------
To quickly turn a URL or email address into a link, enclose it in angle brackets.

MARKDOWN:(<> YH lgany se link or email bn jata)
<https://www.markdownguide.org>
<fake@example.com>

Output:
https://www.markdownguide.org(links bni ayngi yh dono)
fake@example.com

------------------------Formatting Links
To emphasize links, add asterisks before and after the brackets and parentheses. To denote links as code, add backticks in the brackets.

MARKDOWN:
I love supporting the **[EFF](https://eff.org)**.
This is the *[Markdown Guide](https://www.markdownguide.org)*.
See the section on [`code`](#code).(jo #code h yh anchor link h that points to a section within the same document. It links to a heading or element with the ID code. or jo [] is m word
code h wo link to bn jana but code block bhi bnjana kunke ` single backticks hn iske start or end m)

output:
I love supporting the EFF.(EFF yh link to bn jani lekin stearic ** ki madad se EFF bold bhi hojana)
This is the Markdown Guide.(Markdown Guide jo h wo single stearic * ki wjh se italic bn jana)
See the section on code.(code word jo h link or codeblock bn jyga)


-----------------Reference-style Links
Reference-style links are a special kind of link that make URLs easier to display and read in Markdown. Reference-style links are constructed in two parts: the part you keep inline 
with your text and the part you store somewhere else in the file to keep the text easy to read.

How it works:
They have two parts:
The first part is the text with a label ‚Üí [text][label](text or link ky brackets ky beech m space na ho)
The second part is the link definition ‚Üí [label]: URL "optional title"

Why use it:
Instead of putting long, messy URLs in your main text, you move them to the bottom (like footnotes).


----------------------------------example:
This is a [Markdown Guide][1].
[1]: https://www.markdownguide.org "Markdown Guide"

Result:
This is a Markdown Guide.(Markdown Guide link bn gya h or us per hover krny se Markdown Guide likha ayga)


example:
[hobbit-hole][1]   (hobbit-hole link bn gya h or nichy waly m se koi bhi choose kro link hi bnega)

----The optional title for the link, which you can enclose in double quotes, single quotes, or parentheses.
This means the following example formats are all roughly equivalent for the second part of the link:(nichy waly sb krskty sb titles ki types hn)
[1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit#Lifestyle
[1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit#Lifestyle "Hobbit lifestyles"
[1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit#Lifestyle 'Hobbit lifestyles'
[1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit#Lifestyle (Hobbit lifestyles)
[1]: <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit#Lifestyle> "Hobbit lifestyles"
[1]: <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit#Lifestyle> 'Hobbit lifestyles'
[1]: <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit#Lifestyle> (Hobbit lifestyles)


-----------------An Example Putting the Parts Together--------------------
Say you add a URL as a standard URL link to a paragraph and it looks like this in Markdown:

In a hole in the ground there lived a hobbit. Not a nasty, dirty, wet hole, filled with the ends
of worms and an oozy smell, nor yet a dry, bare, sandy hole with nothing in it to sit down on or to
eat: it was a [hobbit-hole](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit#Lifestyle "Hobbit lifestyles"), and that means comfort.( is pury paragraph m word habbit-hole link bn jana or hover krny
per hobbit lifestyle bhi likha ana)


---------------------another example-------------------------
Though it may point to interesting additional information, the URL as displayed really doesn‚Äôt add much to the existing raw text other than making it harder to read. 
To fix that, you could format the URL like this instead:

In a hole in the ground there lived a hobbit. Not a nasty, dirty, wet hole, filled with the ends
of worms and an oozy smell, nor yet a dry, bare, sandy hole with nothing in it to sit down on or to
eat: it was a [hobbit-hole][1], and that means comfort.

[1]: <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit#Lifestyle> "Hobbit lifestyles"  (yh refrence wala zyada bhtr hoga upr wali example se kunke yh zyada clear or readable h)



-------------------------Link Best Practices (Easy Summary)----------------------
Spaces in URLs:
Markdown doesn‚Äôt handle spaces in web addresses properly.

To fix it, replace every space with %20.
‚úÖ Correct:
[link](https://www.example.com/my%20great%20page)

‚ùå Wrong:
[link](https://www.example.com/my great page)


Parentheses in URLs:
URLs with ( or ) can also break.

Replace them with:
( ‚Üí %28
) ‚Üí %29

‚úÖ Correct:
[a novel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Milagro_Beanfield_War_%28novel%29)

‚ùå Wrong:
[a novel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Milagro_Beanfield_War_(novel))


Alternative Option:
If Markdown has issues with your link, you can safely use HTML <a> tags instead:

<a href="https://www.example.com/my%20great%20page">link</a>


‚úÖ In short:
To make sure links always work in Markdown ‚Äî
Replace spaces with %20
Replace parentheses with %28 and %29
Or use an HTML <a> tag for full compatibility.



Images
To add an image, add an exclamation mark (!), followed by alt text in brackets, and the path or URL to the image asset in parentheses. You can optionally add a title in quotation 
marks after the path or URL.

![The San Juan Mountains are beautiful](/assets/images/san-juan-mountains.jpg "San Juan Mountains")(preview m image ajygi or hover krny per San Juan Mountains yh likha ayga)



--------------------Linking Images------------------------------
To add a link to an image, enclose the Markdown for the image in brackets, and then add the link in parentheses.

[![An old rock in the desert](/assets/images/shiprock.jpg "Shiprock, New Mexico by Beau Rogers")](https://www.flickr.com/photos/beaurogers/31833779864/in/photolist-Qv3rFw-34mt9F-a9Cmfy
