------------------üß© Escaping Characters in Markdown---------------
To show a literal character (that Markdown normally uses for formatting), add a backslash (\) before it.
Example: \* ‚Üí renders as * and not as a bullet point.

Rendered Example:
\* Without the backslash, this would be a bullet in an unordered list.(agr backslash na hoti to * ki wjh se is line ko bullet point smh jata or black circle ajata shuru m kunke hamy 
input m \* lgaya h to * isko as a character hi lega
output :   * Without the backslash, this would be a bullet in an unordered list.

‚úÖ Characters You Can Escape
You can use a backslash (\) to escape these characters:
\ (backslash)
` (backtick)
* (asterisk)
_ (underscore)
{ } (curly braces)
(brackets)
< > (angle brackets)
(parentheses)
# (pound sign)
+ (plus sign)
- (minus sign)
. (dot)
! (exclamation mark)
| (pipe symbol)

üß† Using HTML in Markdown
Markdown allows embedding HTML tags directly in text.
This is useful when:
You prefer HTML syntax for images or text.
You want to change attributes (like color, size, width, etc.).(jese image dalengy to uski width manage krni to html use krskty)

Example:
This **word** is bold. This <em>word</em> is italic.

output:(word bold ajana or word italic bhi hojana
This word is bold. This word is italic.

‚öôÔ∏è HTML Best Practices:
‚ö†Ô∏è Not all Markdown applications support HTML. Some only allow specific tags for security reasons.
Always check your Markdown app‚Äôs documentation for HTML compatibility.
Use blank lines before and after block-level HTML elements like <div>, <table>, <pre>, or <p> for correct formatting.
Avoid indenting HTML tags with spaces or tabs ‚Äî this can break the layout.
You cannot use Markdown syntax inside HTML tags.
Example: <p>italic and **bold**</p> ‚ùå (will not render correctly)

‚úÖ In short:
Use a backslash \ to display Markdown symbols as text, and HTML tags when you need more control over formatting ‚Äî but follow best practices for compatibility and security.



